{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The conversation history passed to the LLM is trimmed to the most recent 10 messages when the full history exceeds the context window.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure boundary is module handoff: trimming logic can be correct in isolation but not actually applied in the request builder that sends messages to the LLM client. No real OS/network/subprocess is required, and correctness does not depend on model output. Rejected higher levels because behavior text is only about payload size/ordering before generation, not real HTTP or LLM judgment.","test_description":"Wire chat handler + history-trimmer + LLM request adapter with a fake LLM transport that captures outgoing payload. Provide >10 prior messages, execute one request, and assert exactly the latest 10 are sent in correct order.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.4,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The generated response addresses the customer's question rather than producing a generic or off-topic reply.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on real LLM output quality (relevance to the user question). A stubbed response would always pass and hide true failures in model behavior/prompting. Rejected Workflow because this behavior evaluates a single generation outcome, not multiple agentic decisions chained as the assertion target.","test_description":"Run real model generation on a curated set of customer questions with conversation context and score response relevance against rubric/labels (human or model-as-judge with guardrails). Fail when responses are generic/off-topic above threshold.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.78,"Workflow":0.12}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The tone re-check correctly identifies when a response is too formal for a casual-tier customer and triggers regeneration.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"The key failure is tone-classification correctness, which depends on model judgment; deterministic mocks hide that. The trigger-to-regenerate wiring is integration-like, but the gating decision itself is agentic. Rejected Workflow because one model decision (tone check) is the correctness pivot; regeneration invocation is a downstream action, not a second judged quality target in this behavior text.","test_description":"Use real tone-check path with casual-tier fixtures and intentionally formal candidate responses. Verify the system flags them and initiates regeneration call; include borderline examples to detect misclassification drift.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.62,"Workflow":0.2}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The full exchange (user message, generated response, any regenerations) is persisted to the database with correct timestamps.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure appears when chat orchestration and persistence layer interact (including regeneration records and timestamp fields). This needs real module wiring and a real/local DB, but not real external network/subprocess beyond local storage semantics. Rejected Agentic because behavior is about persistence correctness, not model output quality.","test_description":"Execute request flow with forced regeneration path against a test DB. Assert one exchange record includes user message, initial response, regeneration entries, and timestamp columns populated/ordered correctly (including created_at progression).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.18,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the tone check triggers regeneration, the second response replaces the first — the customer never sees the rejected draft.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Primary risk is orchestration/state handoff across modules: draft response must be superseded before user-facing delivery. This can be caught with deterministic stubs forcing tone-check trigger and two candidate responses. Rejected Agentic because behavior text scopes correctness to replacement semantics after trigger, not whether model decisions are good.","test_description":"Run end-to-end service wiring with stubbed model outputs: first response marked rejected, second accepted. Assert API/UI payload contains only second response, while audit/persistence may retain first as internal draft. Verify no code path emits first draft to customer channel.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.58,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.25,"Workflow":0.12}}]}
